******
[1] Pennsylvania
Date: Mon 19 Nov 2018
Source: Times Online [edited]
http://www.timesonline.com/news/20181119/pa-health-secretary-warns-about-hepatitis-outbreak


Pennsylvania's secretary of health issued a warning on Mon 19 Nov 2018 about an unusually high number of hepatitis A cases in the state that comes as outbreaks across the country have been occurring over the last 2 years.

"The increase in cases highlights the importance of having a primary care physician who you can speak to if you have concerns over your health," Dr Rachel Levine said in a statement released by Governor Tom Wolf's administration. Levine said there are typically between 40 and 60 hepatitis A cases annually in the state, but so far in 2018, there have been 81 reported cases. The statement said there is "increased concern for the disease spreading to other people across the state," especially among injection and non-injection drug users, men who have sex with other men and the homeless. "Hepatitis A is a highly contagious infection that can be very serious," Levine said. "A conversation with your physician will help determine if you should receive a hepatitis A vaccine."

Hepatitis A affects the liver and can be fatal. Beaver County was at the center of a hepatitis A outbreak in 2003 that killed 3 and sickened more than 600 and which was eventually traced back to Mexican green onions used in the former Chi-Chi's restaurant at the Beaver Valley Mall in Center Township.

The statement also noted that Ohio and West Virginia have seen outbreaks of hepatitis A. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention reports that it has been assisting 12 states, including Ohio and West Virginia, to deal with outbreaks of the disease since March 2017.

[byline: JD Prose]

