[While this is a significant increase in numbers of cases, West Virginia had more cases in the past week. - Mod.LL]

******
[2] West Virginia
Date: Fri 16 Nov 2018
Source: West Virginia Department of Health and Human Resources, Office of Epidemiology and Prevention Services [edited]
https://dhhr.wv.gov/oeps/disease/viral-hepatitis/Pages/hepA_outbreak.aspx


Since March 2018, the West Virginia Bureau for Public Health has reported an increase in the number of confirmed cases of acute hepatitis A virus. This increase in cases has primarily been among injecting and non-injecting drug users, homeless or mobile individuals, and those who have been recently incarcerated. Viral sequencing has linked cases from Kentucky and California.

West Virginia hepatitis A outbreak cases as of 16 Nov 2018
----------------------------------------------------------
Number of cases 1859

Demographics
Age range 12-86
Median age 37
Male 1119 (60.2%)
Hospitalizations 960 (51.6%)
Deaths 5

Risk factors
Co-infection with hepatitis C (information available for 1452 cases) 852 (58.7%)
Co-infection with hepatitis B (information available for 1452 cases) 158 (10.4%)
Reports illicit drug use (information available for 1589 cases) 1178 (74.1%)
Homeless 202 (10.9%)

